{"title_page": "Scottie Hazelton", "text_new": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Scottie Hazelton\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| current_title = Defensive coordinator\n| current_team = [[Michigan State Spartans football|Michigan State]] \n| current_conference = [[Big Ten Conference|Big 10]]\n| current_record = \n| contract = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1973|12|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Brighton, Colorado|Brighton]], [[Colorado]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = \n| player_years1 = 1992\u20131994\n| player_team1 = [[Fort Lewis Skyhawks football|Fort Lewis]]\n| player_positions = [[Linebacker]]\n| coach_years1 = 1996\u20131998\n| coach_team1 = [[Fort Lewis Skyhawks football|Fort Lewis]] (DB)\n| coach_years2 = 1999\n| coach_team2 = Fort Lewis ([[Defensive coordinator|DC]])\n| coach_years3 = 2000\u20132001\n| coach_team3 = [[North Dakota State Bison football|North Dakota State]] ([[Graduate assistant|GA]])\n| coach_years4 = 2002\u20132003\n| coach_team4 = [[St. Olaf Oles football|St. Olaf]] (DB)\n| coach_years5 = 2004\u20132005\n| coach_team5 = [[Missouri Southern Lions football|Missouri Southern State]] (DC)\n| coach_years6 = 2006\n| coach_team6 = [[Michigan Tech Huskies football|Michigan Tech]] (LB)\n| coach_years7 = 2007\u20132009\n| coach_team7 = North Dakota State (DL)\n| coach_years8 = 2010\u20132011\n| coach_team8 = North Dakota State (DC/LB)\n| coach_years9 = 2012\n| coach_team9 = [[USC Trojans football|USC]] (LB)\n| coach_years10 = 2013\n| coach_team10 = [[Nevada Wolf Pack football|Nevada]] (DC)\n| coach_years11 = 2014\u20132016\n| coach_team11 = [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] (assistant LB)\n| coach_years12 = 2017\u20132018\n| coach_team12 = [[Wyoming Cowboys football|Wyoming]] (DC/LB)\n| coach_years13 = 2019\n| coach_team13 = [[Kansas State Wildcats football|Kansas State]] (DC/LB)\n| coach_years14 = 2020\u2013present\n| coach_team14 = [[Michigan State Spartans football|Michigan State]] (DC)\n| overall_record = \n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = \n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''Scott Gregory Hazelton''' (born December 19, 1973) is an [[American football]] coach. He is the [[defensive coordinator]] on [[Mel Tucker]]'s staff at [[Michigan State University]].<ref name=\"scoop\">{{cite news |last1=Barnett |first1=Zach |title=Report: Mel Tucker expected to pluck away Power 5 defensive coordinator |url=https://footballscoop.com/news/report-mel-tucker-expected-to-pluck-away-power-5-defensive-coordinator/ |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |work=footballscoop.com |agency=footballscoop.com |publisher=footballscoop |date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> He was the [[defensive coordinator]] and linebackers coach at [[Kansas State University]].<ref>https://www.kstatesports.com/news/2019/1/22/football-klieman-finalizes-initial-coaching-staff-with-hiring-of-hazelton.aspx</ref> He was previously the defensive coordinator and linebackers coach at the University of Wyoming Cowboys in 2017 and 2018 where he led nationally ranked defenses in both seasons, linebackers coach at USC in 2012 and the defensive coordinator of the [[2011 NCAA Division I FCS football season|2011 FCS National Champions]], [[North Dakota State Bison football|North Dakota State Bison]].<ref name=\"usc.rivals.com\">http://usc.rivals.com/content.asp?CID=1330583</ref> Hazelton was tutored as a defensive coach under the guidance of then [[North Dakota State Bison football|North Dakota State]] head coach and current [[Buffalo Bills]] assistant [[Bob Babich (American football coach)|Bob Babich]] <ref>http://www.gobison.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=2400&ATCLID=204875213</ref> and [[Gus Bradley]] who is a former head coach of the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Jaguars hire Gus Bradley as coach|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/afcsouth/post/_/id/46546/jaguars-hire-gus-bradley-as-coach|work=ESPN.com|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref> former Bison assistant coach,<ref name=\"gobison.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gobison.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=2400&ATCLID=867420 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-02-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120731060749/http://www.gobison.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=2400&ATCLID=867420 |archivedate=2012-07-31 }}</ref> and is currently the defensive coordinator for the [[Los Angeles Chargers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/18521720/los-angeles-chargers-hire-gus-bradley-defensive-coordinator |title=Gus Bradley hired as Chargers' defensive coordinator, source says |last=Williams |first=Eric D.  |date=January 21, 2017 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=August 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nHazelton prepped at [[Horizon High School (Thornton, Colorado)|Horizon High School]] in [[Thornton, Colorado]] from 1989 to 1991.<ref name=\"usc.ocregister.com\">http://usc.ocregister.com/2012/02/16/usc-football-hazelton-sanders-officially-join-staff/104934/</ref>\n\nAfter high school, Hazelton played [[linebacker]] at [[Fort Lewis College]], lettering for three years (1992\u20131994) and earning a degree in exercise science.<ref name=\"usc.ocregister.com\"/>\n\n==Coaching career==\nHazelton coaching career started as a defensive backs coach and interim [[defensive coordinator]] for his alma mater, Fort Lewis.<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/> In 2000, Hazelton became a grad assistant at North Dakota State where he worked closely with Bradley and held that position until after the 2001 season.<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/>\n\nAfter finishing his graduate program, Hazelton moved to [[St. Olaf College]], where he worked as the Oles defensive backs coach for two seasons.<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/>\n\nIn 2004, Hazelton was offered the defensive coordinator position at [[Missouri Southern State University|Missouri Southern State]] and held it for two years<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/> before becoming the linebackers coach at [[Michigan Tech Huskies|Michigan Tech]] in 2006.\n\n==North Dakota State==\nAfter five years of coaching elsewhere, Hazelton returned to North Dakota State as a defensive line coach in 2007.<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/> In his first year back with the Bison he helped the defense rank 18th nationally in third down efficiency (33.3%) and 22nd nationally in rushing defense (126.5 ypg).<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/> This was all highlighted with wins over FBS opponents [[Central Michigan Chippewas football|Central Michigan]] 44\u201314 and [[2007 Minnesota Golden Gophers football team|Minnesota]] 27\u201321.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[[North Dakota State Bison football]]</ref>\n\nA year later the defense led the FCS in pass defense (116.82 ypg), 5th in total defense (254 ypg) and 19th in scoring defense (19.18 ppg).<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/> In regards to his position his players ranked 3rd nationally in sacks (3.36 sacks per game) and 5th in tackles for a loss (8.55 TFL per game).<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/>\n\n2009 was not a good year for the Bison and Hazelton. The defense forced just three interceptions while ranking 90th in scoring defense<ref name=\"usc.ocregister.com\"/> and finished 3\u20138 (2\u20136).<ref>https://admin.xosn.com/pdf8/785194.pdf?ATCLID=205272551&SPSID=11862&SPID=695&DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=2400&KEY=AZACODJWVXENNFN.20110915220504</ref><ref>[[2009 NCAA Division I FCS football season]]</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Hazelton was promoted to defensive coordinator. His defensive unit greatly improved from 2009 as the Bison ranked 7th nationally in scoring defense (18.21 ppg) and turnover margin (+1.07 avg).<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/> As well the defense ranked 15th in pass efficiency and 19th in sacks.<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/>\n\nThe Bison advanced to the NCAA Football Championship Subdivision (FCS) playoffs in 2010 for the first time in school history during Hazelton's inaugural season as defensive coordinator which included a win over Big 12 member [[Kansas Jayhawks football|Kansas]] 6\u20133.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> In their game against the Jayhawks Hazelton's defense forced 3 turnovers and held them to under 300 yards.<ref>https://admin.xosn.com/pdf8/785196.pdf?ATCLID=205272551&SPSID=11862&SPID=695&DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=2400&KEY=AZACODJWVXENNFN.20110915220504</ref>\n\n2011 was a banner year for Hazelton and the Bison as they went on to win the FCS National Championship 17\u20136 over Sam Houston<ref name=\"usc.rivals.com\"/> along with finishing the year with a 14\u20131 (7\u20131) record.<ref>[[2011 NCAA Division I FCS football season]]</ref> During the playoffs the Bison rode their defense as they gave up just 27 points in four games.<ref name=\"usc.rivals.com\"/> The Bison ranked in the top 20 in six different categories<ref name=\"usc.ocregister.com\"/> including 1st nationally in points allowed (12.73 ppg) and tied for 7th in takeaways with 31 in 15 games.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">http://usc.ocregister.com/2012/02/12/reports-usc-hires-lb-db-coaches/104690/</ref> For the second time in four years Hazelton and the Bison beat Big 10 member Minnesota 37\u201324.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n==USC ==\nOn February 12, 2012 Hazelton was hired as the linebackers coach of the [[USC Trojans football|USC Trojans]] under head coach [[Lane Kiffin]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2012-02-12/sports/sfl-report-marvin-sanders-leaving-fau-for-usc-20120212_1_lane-kiffin-fau-defensive-coordinator |title=Defensive coordinator Marvin Sanders leaving FAU for USC |accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref> Hazelton replaced Joe Barry<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/> who became the linebackers coach for the [[San Diego Chargers]] on February 6, 2012.<ref>http://usc.ocregister.com/2012/02/06/chargers-announce-hiring-of-ex-usc-lb-coach/104529/</ref>\n\n==Nevada==\nAfter just one season and less than a year with USC, Hazelton was hired by University of Nevada Wolf Pack head coach [[Brian Polian]] on January 18, 2013 to become the team's defensive coordinator.<ref>http://usc.ocregister.com/2013/01/18/hazelton-reportedly-leaving-usc-staff/113315/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHazelton is married with four children.<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/><ref name=\"Oh Baby!\">{{cite web|title=My Coach Calls Me Chica: Oh Baby!|url=http://mycoachcallsmechica.blogspot.com/2013/01/oh-baby.html|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.kstatesports.com/coaches.aspx?rc=1389 Kansas State profile]\n\n{{2011 NDSU Bison football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hazelton, Scottie}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:Fort Lewis Skyhawks football coaches]]\n[[Category:Fort Lewis Skyhawks football players]]\n[[Category:Jacksonville Jaguars coaches]]\n[[Category:Kansas State Wildcats football coaches]]\n[[Category:Michigan Tech Huskies football coaches]]\n[[Category:Nevada Wolf Pack football coaches]]\n[[Category:North Dakota State Bison football coaches]]\n[[Category:People from Brighton, Colorado]]\n[[Category:People from Thornton, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Colorado]]\n[[Category:St. Olaf Oles football coaches]]\n[[Category:USC Trojans football coaches]]\n[[Category:Wyoming Cowboys football coaches]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Scottie Hazelton\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| current_title = Defensive coordinator\n| current_team = [[Michigan State Spartans football|Michigan State]] \n| current_conference = [[Big Ten Conference|Big 10]]\n| current_record = \n| contract = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1973|12|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Brighton, Colorado|Brighton]], [[Colorado]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = \n| player_years1 = 1992\u20131994\n| player_team1 = [[Fort Lewis Skyhawks football|Fort Lewis]]\n| player_positions = [[Linebacker]]\n| coach_years1 = 1996\u20131998\n| coach_team1 = [[Fort Lewis Skyhawks football|Fort Lewis]] (DB)\n| coach_years2 = 1999\n| coach_team2 = Fort Lewis ([[Defensive coordinator|DC]])\n| coach_years3 = 2000\u20132001\n| coach_team3 = [[North Dakota State Bison football|North Dakota State]] ([[Graduate assistant|GA]])\n| coach_years4 = 2002\u20132003\n| coach_team4 = [[St. Olaf Oles football|St. Olaf]] (DB)\n| coach_years5 = 2004\u20132005\n| coach_team5 = [[Missouri Southern Lions football|Missouri Southern State]] (DC)\n| coach_years6 = 2006\n| coach_team6 = [[Michigan Tech Huskies football|Michigan Tech]] (LB)\n| coach_years7 = 2007\u20132009\n| coach_team7 = North Dakota State (DL)\n| coach_years8 = 2010\u20132011\n| coach_team8 = North Dakota State (DC/LB)\n| coach_years9 = 2012\n| coach_team9 = [[USC Trojans football|USC]] (LB)\n| coach_years10 = 2013\n| coach_team10 = [[Nevada Wolf Pack football|Nevada]] (DC)\n| coach_years11 = 2014\u20132016\n| coach_team11 = [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] (assistant LB)\n| coach_years12 = 2017\u20132018\n| coach_team12 = [[Wyoming Cowboys football|Wyoming]] (DC/LB)\n| coach_years13 = 2019\n| coach_team13 = [[Kansas State Wildcats football|Kansas State]] (DC/LB)\n| coach_years14 = 2020\u2013present\n| coach_team14 = [[Michigan State Spartans football|Michigan State]] (DC)\n| overall_record = \n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = \n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''Scott Gregory Hazelton''' (born December 19, 1973) is an [[American football]] coach. He is the [[defensive coordinator]] on [[Mel Tucker]]'s staff at [[Michigan State University]].<ref name=\"scoop\">{{cite news |last1=Barnett |first1=Zach |title=Report: Mel Tucker expected to pluck away Power 5 defensive coordinator |url=https://footballscoop.com/news/report-mel-tucker-expected-to-pluck-away-power-5-defensive-coordinator/ |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |work=footballscoop.com |agency=footballscoop.com |publisher=footballscoop |date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> He was the [[defensive coordinator]] and linebackers coach at [[Kansas State University]].<ref>https://www.kstatesports.com/news/2019/1/22/football-klieman-finalizes-initial-coaching-staff-with-hiring-of-hazelton.aspx</ref> He was previously the defensive coordinator and linebackers coach at the University of Wyoming Cowboys in 2017 and 2018 where he led nationally ranked defenses in both seasons, linebackers coach at USC in 2012 and the defensive coordinator of the [[2011 NCAA Division I FCS football season|2011 FCS National Champions]], [[North Dakota State Bison football|North Dakota State Bison]].<ref name=\"usc.rivals.com\">http://usc.rivals.com/content.asp?CID=1330583</ref> Hazelton was tutored as a defensive coach under the guidance of then [[North Dakota State Bison football|North Dakota State]] head coach and current [[Buffalo Bills]] assistant [[Bob Babich (American football coach)|Bob Babich]] <ref>http://www.gobison.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=2400&ATCLID=204875213</ref> and [[Gus Bradley]] who is a former head coach of the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Jaguars hire Gus Bradley as coach|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/afcsouth/post/_/id/46546/jaguars-hire-gus-bradley-as-coach|work=ESPN.com|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref> former Bison assistant coach,<ref name=\"gobison.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gobison.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=2400&ATCLID=867420 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-02-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120731060749/http://www.gobison.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=2400&ATCLID=867420 |archivedate=2012-07-31 }}</ref> and is currently the defensive coordinator for the [[Los Angeles Chargers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/18521720/los-angeles-chargers-hire-gus-bradley-defensive-coordinator |title=Gus Bradley hired as Chargers' defensive coordinator, source says |last=Williams |first=Eric D.  |date=January 21, 2017 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=August 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nHazelton prepped at [[Horizon High School (Thornton, Colorado)|Horizon High School]] in [[Thornton, Colorado]] from 1989 to 1991.<ref name=\"usc.ocregister.com\">http://usc.ocregister.com/2012/02/16/usc-football-hazelton-sanders-officially-join-staff/104934/</ref>\n\nAfter high school, Hazelton played [[linebacker]] at [[Fort Lewis College]], lettering for three years (1992\u20131994) and earning a degree in exercise science.<ref name=\"usc.ocregister.com\"/>\n\n==Coaching career==\nHazelton coaching career started as a defensive backs coach and interim [[defensive coordinator]] for his alma mater, Fort Lewis.<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/> In 2000, Hazelton became a grad assistant at North Dakota State where he worked closely with Bradley and held that position until after the 2001 season.<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/>\n\nAfter finishing his graduate program, Hazelton moved to [[St. Olaf College]], where he worked as the Oles defensive backs coach for two seasons.<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/>\n\nIn 2004, Hazelton was offered the defensive coordinator position at [[Missouri Southern State University|Missouri Southern State]] and held it for two years<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/> before becoming the linebackers coach at [[Michigan Tech Huskies|Michigan Tech]] in 2006.\n\n==North Dakota State==\nAfter five years of coaching elsewhere, Hazelton returned to North Dakota State as a defensive line coach in 2007.<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/> In his first year back with the Bison he helped the defense rank 18th nationally in third down efficiency (33.3%) and 22nd nationally in rushing defense (126.5 ypg).<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/> This was all highlighted with wins over FBS opponents [[Central Michigan Chippewas football|Central Michigan]] 44\u201314 and [[2007 Minnesota Golden Gophers football team|Minnesota]] 27\u201321.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[[North Dakota State Bison football]]</ref>\n\nA year later the defense led the FCS in pass defense (116.82 ypg), 5th in total defense (254 ypg) and 19th in scoring defense (19.18 ppg).<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/> In regards to his position his players ranked 3rd nationally in sacks (3.36 sacks per game) and 5th in tackles for a loss (8.55 TFL per game).<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/>\n\n2009 was not a good year for the Bison and Hazelton. The defense forced just three interceptions while ranking 90th in scoring defense<ref name=\"usc.ocregister.com\"/> and finished 3\u20138 (2\u20136).<ref>https://admin.xosn.com/pdf8/785194.pdf?ATCLID=205272551&SPSID=11862&SPID=695&DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=2400&KEY=AZACODJWVXENNFN.20110915220504</ref><ref>[[2009 NCAA Division I FCS football season]]</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Hazelton was promoted to defensive coordinator. His defensive unit greatly improved from 2009 as the Bison ranked 7th nationally in scoring defense (18.21 ppg) and turnover margin (+1.07 avg).<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/> As well the defense ranked 15th in pass efficiency and 19th in sacks.<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/>\n\nThe Bison advanced to the NCAA Football Championship Subdivision (FCS) playoffs in 2010 for the first time in school history during Hazelton's inaugural season as defensive coordinator which included a win over Big 12 member [[Kansas Jayhawks football|Kansas]] 6\u20133.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> In their game against the Jayhawks Hazelton's defense forced 3 turnovers and held them to under 300 yards.<ref>https://admin.xosn.com/pdf8/785196.pdf?ATCLID=205272551&SPSID=11862&SPID=695&DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=2400&KEY=AZACODJWVXENNFN.20110915220504</ref>\n\n2011 was a banner year for Hazelton and the Bison as they went on to win the FCS National Championship 17\u20136 over Sam Houston<ref name=\"usc.rivals.com\"/> along with finishing the year with a 14\u20131 (7\u20131) record.<ref>[[2011 NCAA Division I FCS football season]]</ref> During the playoffs the Bison rode their defense as they gave up just 27 points in four games.<ref name=\"usc.rivals.com\"/> The Bison ranked in the top 20 in six different categories<ref name=\"usc.ocregister.com\"/> including 1st nationally in points allowed (12.73 ppg) and tied for 7th in takeaways with 31 in 15 games.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">http://usc.ocregister.com/2012/02/12/reports-usc-hires-lb-db-coaches/104690/</ref> For the second time in four years Hazelton and the Bison beat Big 10 member Minnesota 37\u201324.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n==USC ==\nOn February 12, 2012 Hazelton was hired as the linebackers coach of the [[USC Trojans football|USC Trojans]] under head coach [[Lane Kiffin]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2012-02-12/sports/sfl-report-marvin-sanders-leaving-fau-for-usc-20120212_1_lane-kiffin-fau-defensive-coordinator |title=Defensive coordinator Marvin Sanders leaving FAU for USC |accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref> Hazelton replaced Joe Barry<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/> who became the linebackers coach for the [[San Diego Chargers]] on February 6, 2012.<ref>http://usc.ocregister.com/2012/02/06/chargers-announce-hiring-of-ex-usc-lb-coach/104529/</ref>\n\n==Nevada==\nAfter just one season and less than a year with USC, Hazelton was hired by University of Nevada Wolf Pack head coach [[Brian Polian]] on January 18, 2013 to become the teams defensive coordinator.<ref>http://usc.ocregister.com/2013/01/18/hazelton-reportedly-leaving-usc-staff/113315/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHazelton is married with four children.<ref name=\"gobison.com\"/><ref name=\"Oh Baby!\">{{cite web|title=My Coach Calls Me Chica: Oh Baby!|url=http://mycoachcallsmechica.blogspot.com/2013/01/oh-baby.html|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.kstatesports.com/coaches.aspx?rc=1389 Kansas State profile]\n\n{{2011 NDSU Bison football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hazelton, Scottie}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:Fort Lewis Skyhawks football coaches]]\n[[Category:Fort Lewis Skyhawks football players]]\n[[Category:Jacksonville Jaguars coaches]]\n[[C