otball)|center]]. He played [[college football]] for the [[Tennessee Volunteers football|University of Tennessee]], and was drafted by the [[Green Bay Packers]] in the seventh round of the [[2004 NFL Draft]]. He won [[Super Bowl XLV]] with the Packers over the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]].\n\n==Early years==\nWells's father was in the [[Minister (Christianity)|ministry]] of the [[Churches of Christ]], and Wells began playing football in [[Crowley, Texas]],<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.crowleystar.net/Index.asp?Story=2381 |title = Super Bowl: Packers Wells center honed skills in Crowley |first = Ricky |last = Moore |accessdate = February 4, 2011 |date = February 2, 2011 |newspaper = Crowley Star |place = Crowley, Texas |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110723060356/http://www.crowleystar.net/Index.asp?Story=2381 |archive-date = July 23, 2011 |url-status = dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref> before the family moved to a congregation in [[Pennsylvania]], where Wells spent his freshman and sophomore years at [[Brookville, Pennsylvania|Brookville]] Area High School''';''' he  finished his high school career at [[Brentwood Academy]] in [[Tennessee]]. Wells played [[offensive guard]], [[defensive end]], and [[nose tackle]]. He was a PrepStar and [[CNN]]/''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' [[All America]] selection along with earning the Division II Class A 'Mr. Football' in 1998.\n\nWells also excelled on the wrestling mat, winning two Tennessee State Titles in the 275 pound weight class, going undefeated during his junior and senior years.\n<ref>{{cite web | title = Packers.com Scott Wells Biography | url=http://www.packers.com/team/players/wells_scott/ | accessdate = April 1, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080329034408/http://www.packers.com/team/players/wells_scott/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = March 29, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n\nWells played [[college football]] at the [[Tennessee Volunteers football|University of Tennessee]]. While playing at [[University of Tennessee|Tennessee]] during 2000\u20132003, he was a four-year [[letterman (sports)|letter winner]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Packers.com Scott Wells Biography | url=http://www.packers.com/team/players/wells_scott/ | accessdate = April 1, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080329034408/http://www.packers.com/team/players/wells_scott/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = March 29, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Green Bay Packers===\n[[File:Scott Wells.jpg|thumb|left|210px|upright=3.|Scott Wells playing for Green Bay.]]\nWells was drafted by the [[Green Bay Packers]] in the seventh round, pick 251, of the [[2004 NFL Draft]].\n\nOn September 5, 2004, Wells was waived by the Green Bay Packers but was signed to their [[practice squad]] two-days later on September 7.\n\nOn October 2, 2004, he was promoted to the active roster when [[Mike Flanagan (American football)|Mike Flanagan]] was put on [[injured reserve]].\n\nWells saw his first NFL regular season playing time on [[special teams]] on November 21, 2004, in [[Houston Texans|Houston]]. He was named the starting center in the spring of 2006,<ref name=\"Packers.com Scott Wells Biography\">{{cite web|title=Packers.com Scott Wells Biography |url=http://www.packers.com/team/players/wells_scott/ |accessdate=January 15, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219191251/http://www.packers.com/team/players/wells_scott/ |archivedate=December 19, 2008 }}</ref> and held that position until 2011,<ref>{{cite web | title = CBSSports.com Scott Wells Player Profile | url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/players/playerpage/493110 | accessdate = January 15, 2009}}</ref> missing just one game because of an eye injury.<ref name=\"Packers.com Scott Wells Biography\"/> In November 2006, Scott was given a 5-year, $15 million contract extension.<ref>{{cite web | title = Milwaukee, Wisconsin Journal Sentinel \"Packers Lock Up Wells\" | url=http://www.jsonline.com/sports/packers/29200339.html | accessdate = January 15, 2009}}</ref> At the end of the 2010 season, Wells and the Packers appeared in [[Super Bowl XLV]]. He was a starter in the 31\u201325 victory over the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201102060pit.htm |title=Super Bowl XLV - Pittsburgh Steelers vs. Green Bay Packers - February 6th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 15, 2017}}</ref> On December 26, 2011, Wells was voted to his first career [[2012 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]].\n\n===St. Louis Rams===\nWells signed a 4-year $24 million deal with the St. Louis Rams on March 16, 2012.<ref>[http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2012/03/16/rams-land-scott-wells-to-play-center/ Rams land Scott Wells to play center]</ref> In Week 1 against the [[Detroit Lions]] on September 9, 2012, Wells fractured a metatarsal in his left foot. He also underwent arthroscopic surgery in his right knee to repair some torn cartilage.\n\nWells was released along with [[Jake Long]] on the eve of free agency on March 9, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Thomas|first1=Jim|title=Rams release Jake Long, Scott Wells|url=http://www.stltoday.com/sports/football/professional/rams-release-jake-long-scott-wells/article_5f9d3e00-7a88-5ff1-b9cd-3122c416e62b.html|publisher=stltoday.com|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWells is married to Julie Crosthwait Wells (born 1981), and they have had a son Jackson (born 2004), a daughter Lola (born 2006), and a son Kingston (born 2010).<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.tennessean.com/article/20110203/SPORTS01/102030315/2072/sports%20\n|first = Jim |last = Wyatt |title = Green Bay Packers center Scott Wells is all heart: Brentwood Academy and UT product has overcome doubters, personal tragedy |date = February 3, 2011|accessdate = February 4, 2011|newspaper = Nashville Tennesean }}</ref> The couple had lost premature twin sons, Deacon Scott Wells and Maddox Scott Wells as a result of [[stillbirth]]  on November 24, 2005<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.comdoc/1G1-165232579.html?key=01-42160D517E19126C1109001A01674B2E224E324D3417295C30420B61651B617F137019731B7B1D6B39 |title = Healing power Packers center Scott Wells and his wife, Julie, still cope with the loss of stillborn twin sons in 2005: the family, including 3-year-old Jackson, has since welcomed 8-month-old Lola into their lives|first = Jason |last = Wilde |newspaper = Wisconsin State Journal |place = Madison, Wisconsin|date = June 2007|accessdate = February 4, 2011}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CJa5hXhSG7E ESPN - A Hand for Scott Wells ]</ref> the year before Lola's birth.<ref>{{cite web | title = Packers.com Scott Wells Biography | url=http://www.packers.com/team/players/wells_scott/ | accessdate = April 1, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080329034408/http://www.packers.com/team/players/wells_scott/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = March 29, 2008}}</ref> In 2012, the Wells adopted three children from Uganda, ages 2 through 5 - Caroline, Elijah, and R.J.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stltoday.com/sports/football/professional/scott-wells-goes-extra-mile-for-children/article_1ef15ea4-7621-50aa-bf2d-809849cc47a5.html\n|first=Jim |last=Thomas |title=Scott Wells goes extra mile for children |date=August 27, 2012 |accessdate=November 25, 2012 |newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/writers/jon_wertheim/11/21/scott-wells/index.html\n|first=Jon |last=Wertheim |title=After tragic loss, Wells family finds joy by adopting Ugandan orphans |date=November 21, 2012 |accessdate=November 25, 2012 |publisher=Sports Illustrated.com}}</ref> Caroline was revealed in 2011 to be the biological sister to R.J.<ref name=\":0\" />  The Wells are actively involved in [[Churches of Christ]].<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.christianchronicle.org/blog/2011/02/church-of-christ-preachers-son-starts-at-center-for-green-bay-packer/ |first = Bobby |last = Ross Jr. |newspaper = Christian Chronicle |date = February 4, 2011 |accessdate = February 4, 2011 |title = Church of Christ preacher's son starts at center for Green Bay Packers |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110207212918/http://www.christianchronicle.org/blog/2011/02/church-of-christ-preachers-son-starts-at-center-for-green-bay-packer/ |archive-date = February 7, 2011 |url-status = dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHe has earned two B.A. degrees in history and sociology.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Scott Wells}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101101223455/http://www.packers.com/team/roster/Scott-Wells/dfe3cf21-3ede-4e52-9c8a-c967967a3ff8 Green Bay Packers bio] \n\n{{Packers2004DraftPicks}}\n{{Super Bowl XLV}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wells, Scott}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Spring Hill, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:American members of the Churches of Christ]]\n[[Category:American football centers]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Volunteers football players]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Rams players]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: Tennesean \u2192 Tennessean", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scott_Wells"}
{"title_page": "Valery Legasov", "text_new": "{{short description|Soviet chemist, chief of the Chernobyl disaster investigation commission}}\n{{Expand language|topic=|langcode=ru|otherarticle=|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n |honorific_suffix =\n |name          = Valery Legasov\n |image         = Legasov (inorganic chemist).jpg\n |alt           = Photograph\n |birth_name    = Valery Alekseyevich Legasov\n |birth_date    = {{birth date|df=y|1936|9|1}}\n |death_date    = {{nowr|{{dda|df=y|1988|4|27|1936|9|1}}}}\n |birth_place   = [[Tula, Russia|Tula]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian SFSR]], [[Soviet Union]]\n |death_place   = [[Moscow]], Russian SFSR, Soviet Union\n |resting_place = [[Novodevichy Cemetery]], Moscow\n |death_cause   = [[Suicide]] by [[hanging]]\n |alma_mater    = [[D. Mendeleev University of Chemical Technology of Russia]]\n |known_for     = Chief of the commission investigating the Chernobyl disaster\n |spouse        = \n |children      = Inga Legasova<ref>{{cite book |title= Midnight in Chernobyl: The Untold Story of the World's Greatest Nuclear Disaster |first= Adam |last= Higginbotham |year= 2019 |publisher= [[Simon and Schuster]] |isbn= 9781501134616 |location= New York |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/midnightincherno0000higg }}</ref>\n |awards        = [[Hero of the Russian Federation]] (posthumous)<br/>[[Order of Lenin]]<br/>[[Order of the Red Banner of Labour]]\n |field         = [[Nuclear physics]]\n |workplaces    = [[Kurchatov Institute of Atomic Energy]]<br/>[[Moscow Institute of Physics and Technology]]<br/>[[Moscow State University]]<br/>\n |thesis_title  = \n |thesis_url    = \n |thesis_year   = \n |doctoral_advisor  = Isaak Kikoin\n |academic_advisors = \n |doctoral_students = \n |notable_students  =\n |influences    = \n |influenced    = \n |signature     = \n}}\n'''Valery Alekseyevich Legasov''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041b\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432}}; 1 September 1936 \u2013 27 April 1988) was a Soviet [[inorganic chemist]] and a member of the [[Academy of Sciences of the USSR]]. He is now mainly remembered for his work as the chief of the commission investigating the [[Chernobyl disaster]].<ref name=\"ap-obituary\">{{cite web|title=Chemist, investigator of Chernobyl nuclear accident dies at 51|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1988/Chemist-Investigator-of-Chernobyl-Nuclear-Accident-Dies-at-51/id-c27496263c4c08f7334d2cdbfe65f483|work=AP News Archive|author=The Associated Press|accessdate=26 April 2014|date=April 30, 1988|quote=[the official Soviet news agency] Tass said Legasov made a \"significant contribution in the working out and realization of immediate measures aimed at liquidating the consequences of the accident.\"}}</ref>\n\n== Biography==\n{{more citations needed section|date=June 2019}}\nLegasov was born on September 1, 1936, in [[Tula, Russia|Tula]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian SFSR]], into a family of civil workers.<ref name=\"newtimes\">{{cite book|title=New Times|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G_FVAAAAYAAJ|page=58|year=1996|publisher=New Times Publishing House}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UoPVBgAAQBAJ|title=Producing Power: The Pre-Chernobyl History of the Soviet Nuclear Industry|first1=Sonja D. |last1=Schmid|year=2015|isbn=9780262028271}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=American Association for the Advancement of Slavic Studies|year=1988|page=24|title=The Current Digest of the Soviet Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=byrvAAAAMAAJ}}</ref> He attended secondary school in [[Kursk]].<ref name=\"newtimes\" /> In 1949\u20131954, he attended School No. 56 in Moscow and graduated with a gold medal.<ref name=\"newtimes\" /> The school now bears his name, and his bronze bust stands at the entrance. He married Margarita Mikhailovna and had a daughter, Inga Legasova.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0443\u0431\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u041b\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0430, \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043b \u0441\u043e\u0431\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0427\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0431\u044b\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u044b |url=https://www.mk.ru/social/2017/04/25/kak-ubivali-akademika-legasova-kotoryy-provel-sobstvennoe-rassledovanie-chernobylskoy-katastrofy.html |work=www.mk.ru |language=ru}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Higginbotham |first1=Adam |title=Midnight in Chernobyl: The Untold Story of the World's Greatest Nuclear Disaster |date=2019 |publisher=Simon and Schuster |isbn=9781501134616 |url=https://archive.org/details/midnightincherno0000higg |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/midnightincherno0000higg/page/423 423] |quote=Inga Legasova. |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Choiniere |first1=Alyssa |title=Valery Legasov: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know |url=https://heavy.com/news/2019/06/valery-legasov/ |website=Heavy.com |language=en |date=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1961, he graduated from the Faculty of Physicochemical Engineering at the [[Mendeleev Moscow Institute of Chemistry and Technology]].<ref name=\"Marples\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JJqvCwAAQBAJ|title=Ukraine under Perestroika: Ecology, Economics and the Workers' Revolt|first1=David|last1=Marples|page=21|year=1991|authorlink1=David R. Marples|isbn=9781349108800}}</ref>\n\nHe worked{{When|date=May 2019}} as secretary of the [[Komsomol]] Committee of the Moscow Institute of Chemical Technology.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nIn 1962, he joined the graduate school in the Department of Molecular Physics of the [[Kurchatov Institute of Atomic Energy]],<ref name=\"redatom\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y3MJq8w8sKsC|title=Red Atom: Russia's Nuclear Power Program from Stalin to Today|last1=Josephson|first1=Paul R.|year=2005|isbn=9780822978473}}</ref>{{rp|261}} first as a junior then senior researcher, and finally as head of the laboratory.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} In 1967,{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} he defended his thesis at the Kurchatov Institute, under the supervisor [[Isaac Kikoin]], on the synthesis of compounds of [[noble gas]]es and the study of their properties{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}.<ref name='redatom'/>{{rp|261}} He received the degree of [[Kandidat|candidate]] in 1967 and his [[doctorate]] in [[chemistry]] in 1972.<ref>{{cite book| author = {{nobr|\u0411\u043e\u0433\u0443\u043d\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u041d. \u041d.}}, {{nobr|\u041f\u0438\u043b\u0438\u043f\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0410. \u0414.}}, {{nobr|\u0421\u043e\u0441\u043d\u0438\u043d \u0413. \u0410.}} | chapter = | chapter-url = | format = | url =  | title = \u0413\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0438 \u0430\u0442\u043e\u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 | orig-year = | agency =  | edition =  {{nowrap|3000 \u044d\u043a\u0437}} |location= \u0421\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432 |date = 2005 |publisher= \u0424\u0413\u0423\u041f \u00ab\u0420\u0424\u042f\u0426-\u0412\u041d\u0418\u0418\u042d\u0424\u00bb |volume=  | page = 448 | series =  | isbn = 5-9515-0005-2| ref = \u0411\u043e\u0433\u0443\u043d\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0438 \u0434\u0440.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1976, he was elected a corresponding member of the [[Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union|Academy of Sciences of the USSR]].{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nFrom 1978 to 1983, he was a professor at the [[Moscow Institute of Physics and Technology]].<ref name=\"schmid\">{{cite book |last1=D. Schmid |first1=Sonja |title=Producing Power: The Pre-Chernobyl History of the Soviet Nuclear Industry |date=2015 |publisher=MIT Press |isbn=978-0262028271 |page=[https://archive.org/details/producingpowerpr0000schm/page/182 182] |url=https://archive.org/details/producingpowerpr0000schm|url-access=registration }}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, he became a full member of the Academy of Sciences of the USSR, in the Department of Physical Chemistry and Technology of Inorganic Materials.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nFrom 1983 until his death, he worked as chair of the department of Radiochemistry and Chemical Technology at the Faculty of Chemistry at Moscow State University.<ref name=\"schmid\"/> In 1983,<ref name=\"schmid\"/> he became the first Deputy Director for scientific work of the Kurchatov Institute of Atomic Energy.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ogYAAAAAMBAJ|title=A Soviet Expert Discusses Chernobyl|year=1987|journal=Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists|volume=43|issue=6|page=32|bibcode=1987BuAtS..43f..32L|last1=Legasov|first1=Valery|doi=10.1080/00963402.1987.11459553}}</ref>\n\nLegasov studied methods for the synthesis and the properties of new compounds with elements in high oxidation states; nuclear and plasma technology; energy-saving technology, and hydrogen energy.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} Under his leadership, a scientific school was created in the newest section of inorganic chemistry \u2013 chemistry of noble gases.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nEven before the Chernobyl disaster, Legasov was known to stress the need for new security and safety methods to prevent large catastrophes.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.rbth.com/history/330459-valery-legasov-chernobyl |title = Who was Valery Legasov, the Soviet scientist that saved the world from Chernobyl?|date = 2019-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.mk.ru/social/2017/04/25/kak-ubivali-akademika-legasova-kotoryy-provel-sobstvennoe-rassledovanie-chernobylskoy-katastrofy.html |title = \u041a\u0430\u043a \u0443\u0431\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u041b\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0430, \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043b \u0441\u043e\u0431\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0427\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0431\u044b\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u044b}}</ref>\n\n== Chernobyl disaster ==\n\n[[File:IAEA 02790039 (5612537521).jpg|thumb|Valery Legasov.]]\n\n{{Main|Chernobyl disaster}}\nBy the time of the Chernobyl disaster on 26 April 1986, Legasov was the first deputy director of the Kurchatov Institute of Atomic Energy.<ref>{{cite article|title=Hans Blix: our man in Iraq|first1=David|last1=Marples|url=http://ukrweekly.com/archive/pdf3/2003/The_Ukrainian_Weekly_2003-04.pdf|newspaper= The Ukrainian Weekly|page= 2 |date=2003-01-26|authorlink1=David R. Marples}}</ref> He became a key member of the government commission formed to investigate the causes of the disaster and to plan the mitigation of its consequences. He took the most important decisions to avoid repeat accidents and informed the government of the situation in the disaster area. He did not hesitate to speak to his fellow scientists and to the press about the safety risks of the destroyed plant and insisted on the immediate evacuation of the entire population of the city of [[Prypiat (city)|Pripyat]] nearby. In August 1986, he presented the report of the Soviet delegation at the special meeting of [[International Atomic Energy Agency]] (IAEA) in [[Vienna]]. His report displayed a depth of analysis and honesty in discussing the extent and consequences of the tragedy.<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Bella |last1=Belb\u00e9och |url=http://www.akademia.ch/sebes/textes/1998/98BelbeochB.html |title=Responsabilites Occidentales Dans les Consequences Sanitaires de la Catastrophe de Tchernobyl, en Bielorussie, Ukraine et Russie |journal=Radioprotection et Droit Nucl\u00e9aire  |year=1998|pages=247\u2013261|language=French|trans-title=Western responsibility regarding the health consequences of the Chernobyl catastrophe in Belarus, the Ukraine and Russia}}<br>English translation1:<br>{{cite book |first1=Michael |last1=Fernex |first2=Bella |last2=Belb\u00e9och |title=The Chernobyl catastrophe and health care |chapter=Western responsibility regarding the health consequences of the Chernobyl catastrophe in Belarus, the Ukraine and Russia |chapter-url=http://ru.indymedia.org/usermedia/text/10/western_responsability.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726002457/http://ru.indymedia.org/usermedia/text/10/western_responsability.html |archive-date=2011-07-26 |accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref> Legasov recorded five audio tapes<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://legasovtapetranslation.blogspot.com/|title=The Legasov Tapes|website=legasovtapetranslation.blogspot.com|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>{{better source needed|reason=Blogs are [[WP:NOTRS]].|date=January 2020}} where he expressed his point of view on events that happened in Chernobyl. The fifth and last tape was recorded with [[Ales Adamovich]] as an interview for an article.\n\n== Death ==\n[[File:\u041c\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0412\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0438\u044f \u041b\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0430.JPG|thumb|The grave of Professor Valery Legasov at Novodevichy Cemetery in Moscow.]]\nOn 27 April 1988,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1988-04-30-mn-2023-story.html|title=OBITUARIES : Valery A. Legasov, 51; Chernobyl Investigator|publisher=latimes.com|date=30 April 1988}}</ref> one day after the second anniversary of the [[Chernobyl disaster|Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant accident]] and one day before he was due to announce his results of the investigation into the causes of the disaster, Legasov [[hanged]] himself (some sources say in his apartment<ref name=\"ap-obituary\" /><ref name = nei>{{cite news |title=Legasov suicide leaves unanswered questions |date=July 1988 |journal=Nuclear Engineering International |url=https://www.neimagazine.com/features/featurelegasov-suicide-leaves-unanswered-questions/ |quote=Soviet nuclear industry sources have said that domestic problems played a role, but the timing, 27 April, exactly 2 years after the Chernobyl accident, is clearly of major significance. His death was first officially announced on 29 April, but without any mention of the cause. Subsequently its emerged that he had taken his own life.}}</ref> or the stairwell of his apartment;<ref>{{cite web|website=Media Entertainment Arts WorldWide|title=Scientist who exposed true extent of Chernobyl disaster killed himself a day after second anniversary (As the Deputy Director of Kurchatov Institute of Atomic Energy in Moscow, Valery Legasov received a distress call on 26 April 1986, asking him to head to Chernobyl. His life was never the same.)|author=Tripathi, Namrata |date= May 2, 2019 | url=https://meaww.com/hbo-chernobyl-nuclear-disaster-soviet-specialist-valery-legasov-expose-extent}}</ref> others in his office<ref name=\"Spiegel\">{{cite news |title= 'This Reactor Model Is No Good': Documents Show Politburo Skepticism of Chernobyl |first=Christian |last=Neef |translator-first=Christopher |translator-last=Sultan |journal=[[Der Spiegel]] |date=24 March 2011 |url=https://www.spiegel.de/international/zeitgeist/this-reactor-model-is-no-good-documents-show-politburo-skepticism-of-chernobyl-a-752696.html |quote=But he did not die of radiation sickness, even though he spent four months in Chernobyl after the explosion there. Legasov hanged himself in his office on 27 April 1988, almost two years to the day after the reactor accident in present-day Ukraine.}}</ref>). A personal pistol remained in a drawer, but the professor chose to hang himself. He was buried at the Novodevichy cemetery in Moscow.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/68123592/valeri-alekseevich-legasov |title=Valeri Alekseevich Legasov|website= findagrave.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://novodevichye.com/legasov/ |website=novodevichye.com|title=Legasov's tomb}}</ref>\n\nThis was not Legasov's first suicide attempt.<ref>{{cite web|website=Media Entertainment Arts WorldWide|title=Scientist who exposed true extent of Chernobyl disaster killed himself a day after second anniversary (As the Deputy Director of Kurchatov Institute of Atomic Energy in Moscow, Valery Legasov received a distress call on April 26, 1986, asking him to head to Chernobyl. His life was never the same.)|author=Tripathi, Namrata |date= May 2, 2019 | url=https://meaww.com/hbo-chernobyl-nuclear-disaster-soviet-specialist-valery-legasov-expose-extent}}</ref> [[David R. Marples]] has suggested that the adversity of the Chernobyl disaster on Legasov's psychological state was the factor that led to his decision to die by suicide.<ref name = Marples/> Before his suicide, Legasov wrote documents revealing previously undisclosed facts about the catastrophe.<ref name=\"Spiegel\" /> According to an analysis of the recording for the [[BBC]] TV movie ''Chernobyl Nuclear Disaster'',<ref name=\"BBCdisaster\">{{cite book|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0775665/|title=Surviving Disaster: Chernobyl Nuclear Disaster|publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> Legasov claims political pressure censored the mention of Soviet nuclear secrecy in his report to the IAEA, a secrecy which forbade even plant operators having knowledge of previous accidents and known problems with reactor design.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.world-nuclear.org/information-library/safety-and-security/safety-of-plants/chernobyl-accident.aspx |title = Chernobyl &#124; Chernobyl Accident &#124; Chernobyl Disaster - World Nuclear Association}}</ref> The ''[[Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists]]'' also stated that Legasov had become bitterly disillusioned with the failure of the authorities to confront the design flaws.<ref name=\"the-bulletin\">{{cite journal|title=Chernobyl's Lengthening Shadow |first1=David|last1= Marples |journal=[[The Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists]] |volume=49|issue=7|date=September 1993 |page=40 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pQwAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA40|authorlink1=David R. Marples|bibcode=1993BuAtS..49g..38M|doi=10.1080/00963402.1993.11456385}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nLegasov's suicide caused shockwaves in the Soviet nuclear industry. In particular, the problem with the design of the [[control rod]]s in Chernobyl-type [[RBMK|RBMK reactors]] was rapidly admitted and addressed.<ref name=BBCdisaster /><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.world-nuclear.org/information-library/safety-and-security/safety-of-plants/chernobyl-accident.aspx |title = Chernobyl &#124; Chernobyl Accident &#124; Chernobyl Disaster - World Nuclear Association}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 September 1996, then-Russian president [[Boris Yeltsin]] posthumously conferred on Legasov the honorary title of [[Hero of the Russian Federation]], the country's highest honorary title, for the \"courage and heroism\" shown in his investigation of the disaster.<ref>{{cite book|authors=de Miranda, Paulo Emilio V. | url=https://books.google.com/?id=e5t5DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA352&lpg=PA352&dq=valery+legasov+hero+of+the+russian+federation#v=onepage&q=valery%20legasov%20hero%20of%20the%20russian%20federation&f=false |title= Science and Engineering of Hydrogen-Based Energy Technologies|isbn = 9780128142523|date = 2018-11-12}}</ref>\n\n== In media==\nLegasov is portrayed by [[Ade Edmondson]] in the [[BBC]] [[docudrama]] ''Surviving Disaster'' (2006), and by [[Jared Harris]] in the Sky/HBO miniseries ''[[Chernobyl (miniseries)|Chernobyl]]'' (2019).\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Chernobyl disaster effects]]\n* [[Liquidator (Chernobyl)]]\n* [[List of Chernobyl-related articles]]\n* [[Nuclear and radiation accidents and incidents]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Authority control}}\n{{chernobyl disaster|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Legasov, Valery}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:Heroes of the Russian Federation]]\n[[Category:Lenin Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Full Members of the USSR Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Moscow Institute of Physics and Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Moscow State University faculty]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Chernobyl disaster]]\n[[Category:People from Tula, Russia]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Lenin]]\n[[Category:Scientists who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Soviet chemists]]\n[[Category:20th-century chemists]]\n[[Category:Suicides by hanging in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the USSR State Prize]]\n[[Category:Chernobyl liquidators]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of the Soviet Union members]]\n[[Category:D. Mendeleev University of Chemical Technology of Russia alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Soviet chemist, chief of the Chernobyl disaster investigation commission}}\n{{Expand language|topic=|langcode=ru|otherarticle=|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n |honorific_suffix =\n |name          = Valery Legasov\n |image         = Legasov (inorganic chemist).jpg\n |alt           = Photograph\n |birth_name    = Valery Alekseyevich Legasov\n |birth_date    = {{birth date|df=y|1936|9|1}}\n |death_date    = {{nowr|{{dda|df=y|1988|4|27|1936|9|1}}}}\n |birth_place   = [[Tula, Russia|Tula]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian SFSR]], [[Soviet Union]]\n |death_place   = [[Moscow]], Russian SFSR, Soviet Union\n |resting_place = [[Novodevichy Cemetery]], Moscow\n |death_cause   = [[Suicide]] by [[hanging]]\n |alma_mater    = [[D. Mendeleev University of Chemical Technology of Russia]]\n |known_for     = Chief of the commission investigating the Chernobyl disaster\n |spouse        = \n |children      = Inga Legasova<ref>{{cite book |title= Midnight in Chernobyl: The Untold Story of the World's Greatest Nuclear Disaster |first= Adam |last= Higginbotham |year= 2019 |publisher= [[Simon and Schuster]] |isbn= 9781501134616 |location= New York |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/midnightincherno0000higg }}</ref>\n |awards        = [[Hero of the Russian Federation]] (posthumous)<br/>[[Order of Lenin]]<br/>[[Order of the Red Banner of Labour]]\n |field         = [[Nuclear physics]]\n |workplaces    = [[Kurchatov Institute of Atomic Energy]]<br/>[[Moscow Institute of Physics and Technology]]<br/>[[Moscow State University]]<br/>\n |thesis_title  = \n |thesis_url    = \n |thesis_year   = \n |doctoral_advisor  = Isaak Kikoin\n |academic_advisors = \n |doctoral_students = \n |notable_students  =\n |influences    = \n |influenced    = \n |signature     = \n}}\n'''Valery Alekseyevich Legasov''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041b\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432}}; 1 September 1936 \u2013 27 April 1988) was a Soviet [[inorganic chemist]] and a member of the [[Academy of Sciences of the USSR]]. He is now mainly remembered for his work as the chief of the commission investigating the [[Chernobyl disaster]].<ref name=\"ap-obituary\">{{cite web|title=Chemist, investigator of Chernobyl nuclear accident dies at 51|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1988/Chemist-Investigator-of-Chernobyl-Nuclear-Accident-Dies-at-51/id-c27496263c4c08f7334d2cdbfe65f483|work=AP News Archive|author=The Associated Press|accessdate=26 April 2014|date=April 30, 1988|quote=[the official Soviet news agency] Tass said Legasov made a \"significant contribution in the working out and realization of immediate measures aimed at liquidating the consequences of the accident.\"}}</ref>\n\n== Biography==\n{{more citations needed section|date=June 2019}}\nLegasov was born on September 1, 1936, in [[Tula, Russia|Tula]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian SFSR]], into a family of civil workers.<ref name=\"newtimes\">{{cite book|title=New Times|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G_FVAAAAYAAJ|page=58|year=1996|publisher=New Times Publishing House}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UoPVBgAAQBAJ|title=Producing Power: The Pre-Chernobyl History of the Soviet Nuclear Industry|first1=Sonja D. |last1=Schmid|year=2015|isbn=9780262028271}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=American Association for the Advancement of Slavic Studies|year=1988|page=24|title=The Current Digest of the Soviet Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=byrvAAAAMAAJ}}</ref> He attended secondary school in [[Kursk]].<ref name=\"newtimes\" /> In 1949\u20131954, he attended School No. 56 in Moscow and graduated with a gold medal.<ref name=\"newtimes\" /> The school now bears his name, and his bronze bust stands at the entrance. He married Margarita Mikhailovna and had a daughter, Inga Legasova.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0443\u0431\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u041b\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0430, \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043b \u0441\u043e\u0431\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0427\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0431\u044b\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u044b |url=https://www.mk.ru/social/2017/04/25/kak-ubivali-akademika-legasova-kotoryy-provel-sobstvennoe-rassledovanie-chernobylskoy-katastrofy.html |work=www.mk.ru |language=ru}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Higginbotham |first1=Adam |title=Midnight in Chernobyl: The Untold Story of the World's Greatest Nuclear Disaster |date=2019 |publisher=Simon and Schuster |isbn=9781501134616 |url=https://archive.org/details/midnightincherno0000higg |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/midnightincherno0000higg/page/423 423] |quote=Inga Legasova. |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Choiniere |first1=Alyssa |title=Valery Legasov: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know |url=https://heavy.com/news/2019/06/valery-legasov/ |website=Heavy.com |language=en |date=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1961, he graduated from the Faculty of Physicochemical Engineering at the [[Mendeleev Moscow Institute of Chemistry and Technology]].<ref name=\"Marples\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JJqvCwAAQBAJ|title=Ukraine under Perestroika: Ecology, Economics and the Workers' Revolt|first1=David|last1=Marples|page=21|year=1991|authorlink1=David R. Marples|isbn=9781349108800}}</ref>\n\nHe worked{{When|date=May 2019}} as secretary of the [[Komsomol]] Committee of the Moscow Institute of Chemical Technology.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nIn 1962, he joined the graduate school in the Department of Molecular Physics of the [[Kurchatov Institute of Atomic Energy]],<ref name=\"redatom\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y3MJq8w8sKsC|title=Red Atom: Russia's Nuclear Power Program from Stalin to Today|last1=Josephson|first1=Paul R.|year=2005|isbn=9780822978473}}</ref>{{rp|261}} first as a junior then senior researcher, and finally as head of the laboratory.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} In 1967,{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} he defended his thesis at the Kurchatov Institute, under the supervisor [[Isaac Kikoin]], on the synthesis of compounds of [[noble gas]]es and the study of their properties{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}.<ref name='redatom'/>{{rp|261}} He received the degree of [[Kandidat|candidate]] in 1967 and his [[doctorate]] in [[chemistry]] in 1972.<ref>{{cite book| author = {{nobr|\u0411\u043e\u0433\u0443\u043d\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u041d. \u041d.}}, {{nobr|\u041f\u0438\u043b\u0438\u043f\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0410. \u0414.}}, {{nobr|\u0421\u043e\u0441\u043d\u0438\u043d \u0413. \u0410.}} | chapter = | chapter-url = | format = | url =  | title = \u0413\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0438 \u0430\u0442\u043e\u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 | orig-year = | agency =  | edition =  {{nowrap|3000 \u044d\u043a\u0437}} |location= \u0421\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432 |date = 2005 |publisher= \u0424\u0413\u0423\u041f \u00ab\u0420\u0424\u042f\u0426-\u0412\u041d\u0418\u0418\u042d\u0424\u00bb |volume=  | page = 448 | series =  | isbn = 5-9515-0005-2| ref = \u0411\u043e\u0433\u0443\u043d\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0438 \u0434\u0440.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1976, he was elected a corresponding member of the [[Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union|Academy of Sciences of the USSR]].{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nFrom 1978 to 1983, he was a professor at the [[Moscow Institute of Physics and Technology]].<ref name=\"schmid\">{{cite book |last1=D. Schmid |first1=Sonja |title=Producing Power: The Pre-Chernobyl History of the Soviet Nuclear Industry |date=2015 |publisher=MIT Press |isbn=978-0262028271 |page=[https://archive.org/details/producingpowerpr0000schm/page/182 182] |url=https://archive.org/details/producingpowerpr0000schm|url-access=registration }}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, he became a full member of the Academy of Sciences of the USSR, in the Department of Physical Chemistry and Technology of Inorganic Materials.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nFrom 1983 until his death, he worked as chair of the department of Radiochemistry and Chemical Technology at the Faculty of Chemistry at Moscow State University.<ref name=\"schmid\"/> In 1983,<ref name=\"schmid\"/> he became the first Deputy Director for scientific work of the Kurchatov Institute of Atomic Energy.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ogYAAAAAMBAJ|title=A Soviet Expert Discusses Chernobyl|year=1987|journal=Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists|volume=43|issue=6|page=32|bibcode=1987BuAtS..43f..32L|last1=Legasov|first1=Valery|doi=10.1080/00963402.1987.11459553}}</ref>\n\nLegasov studied methods for the synthesis and the properties of new compounds with elements in high oxidation states; nuclear and plasma technology; energy-saving technology, and hydrogen energy.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} Under his leadership, a scientific school was created in the newest section of inorganic chemistry \u2013 chemistry of noble gases.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nEven before the Chernobyl disaster, Legasov was known to stress the need for new security and safety methods to prevent large catastrophes.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.rbth.com/history/330459-valery-legasov-chernobyl |title = Who was Valery Legasov, the Soviet scientist that saved the world from Chernobyl?|date = 2019-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.mk.ru/social/2017/04/25/kak-ubivali-akademika-legasova-kotoryy-provel-sobstvennoe-rassledovanie-chernobylskoy-katastrofy.html |title = \u041a\u0430\u043a \u0443\u0431\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u041b\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0430, \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043b \u0441\u043e\u0431\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0427\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0431\u044b\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u044b}}</ref>\n\n== Chernobyl disaster ==\n\n[[File:IAEA 02790039 (5612537521).jpg|thumb|Valery Legasov.]]\n\n{{Main|Chernobyl disaster}}\nBy the time of the Chernobyl disaster on 26 April 1986, Legasov was the first deputy director of the Kurchatov Institute of Atomic Energy.<ref>{{cite article|title=Hans Blix: our man in Iraq|first1=David|last1=Marples|url=http://ukrweekly.com/archive/pdf3/2003/The_Ukrainian_Weekly_2003-04.pdf|newspaper= The Ukrainian Weekly|page= 2 |date=2003-01-26|authorlink1=David R. Marples}}</ref> He became a key member of the government commission formed to investigate the causes of the disaster and to plan the mitigation of its consequences. He took the most important decisions to avoid repeat accidents and informed the government of the situation in the disaster area. He did not hesitate to speak to his fellow scientists and to the press about the safety risks of the destroyed plant and insisted on the immediate evacuation of the entire population of the city of [[Prypiat (city)|Pripyat]] nearby. In August 1986, he presented the report of the Soviet delegation at the special meeting of [[International Atomic Energy Agency]] (IAEA) in [[Vienna]]. His report displayed a depth of analysis and honesty in discussing the extent and consequences of the tragedy.<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Bella |last1=Belb\u00e9och |url=http://www.akademia.ch/sebes/textes/1998/98BelbeochB.html |title=Responsabilites Occidentales Dans les Consequences Sanitaires de la Catastrophe de Tchernobyl, en Bielorussie, Ukraine et Russie |journal=Radioprotection et Droit Nucl\u00e9aire  |year=1998|pages=247\u2013261|language=French|trans-title=Western responsibility regarding the health consequences of the Chernobyl catastrophe in Belarus, the Ukraine and Russia}}<br>English translation1:<br>{{cite book |first1=Michael |last1=Fernex |first2=Bella |last2=Belb\u00e9och |title=The Chernobyl catastrophe and health care |chapter=Western responsibility regarding the health consequences of the Chernobyl catastrophe in Belarus, the Ukraine and Russia |chapter-url=http://ru.indymedia.org/usermedia/text/10/western_responsability.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726002457/http://ru.indymedia.org/usermedia/text/10/western_responsability.html |archive-date=2011-07-26 |accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref> Legasov recorded 5 audio tapes<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://legasovtapetranslation.blogspot.com/|title=The Legasov Tapes|website=legasovtapetranslation.blogspot.com|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>{{better source needed|reason=Blogs are [[WP:NOTRS]].|date=January 2020}} where he expressed his point of view on events that happened in Chernobyl. The 5th and last tape was recorded with [[Ales Adamovich]] as an interview for an article.\n\n== Death ==\n[[File:\u041c\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0412\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0438\u044f \u041b\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0430.JPG|thumb|The grave of Professor Valery Legasov at Novodevichy Cemetery in Moscow.]]\nOn 27 April 1988,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1988-04-30-mn-2023-story.html|title=OBITUARIES : Valery A. Legasov, 51; Chernobyl Investigator|publisher=latimes.com|date=30 April 1988}}</ref> one day after the second anniversary of the [[Chernobyl disaster|Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant accident]] and one day before he was due to announce his results of the investigation into the causes of the disaster, Legasov [[hanged]] himself (some sources say in his apartment<ref name=\"ap-obituary\" /><ref name = nei>{{cite news |title=Legasov suicide leaves unanswered questions |date=July 1988 |journal=Nuclear Engineering International |url=https://www.neimagazine.com/features/featurelegasov-suicide-leaves-unanswered-questions/ |quote=Soviet nuclear industry sources have said that domestic problems played a role, but the timing, 27 April, exactly 2 years after the Chernobyl accident, is clearly of major significance. His death was first officially announced on 29 April, but without any mention of the cause. Subsequently its emerged that he had taken his own life.}}</ref> or the stairwell of his apartment;<ref>{{cite web|website=Media Entertainment Arts WorldWide|title=Scientist who exposed true extent of Chernobyl disaster killed himself a day after second anniversary (As the Deputy Director of Kurchatov Institute of Atomic Energy in Moscow, Valery Legasov received a distress call on 26 April 1986, asking him to head to Chernobyl. His life was never the same.)|author=Tripathi, Namrata |date= May 2, 2019 | url=https://meaww.com/hbo-chernobyl-nuclear-disaster-soviet-specialist-valery-legasov-expose-extent}}</ref> others in his office<ref name=\"Spiegel\">{{cite news |title= 'This Reactor Model Is No Good': Documents Show Politburo Skepticism of Chernobyl |first=Christian |last=Neef |translator-first=Christopher |translator-last=Sultan |journal=[[Der Spiegel]] |date=24 March 2011 |url=https://www.spiegel.de/international/zeitgeist/this-reactor-model-is-no-good-documents-show-politburo-skepticism-of-chernobyl-a-752696.html |quote=But he did not die of radiation sickness, even though he spent four months in Chernobyl after the explosion there. Legasov hanged himself in his office on 27 April 1988, almost two years to the day after the reactor accident in present-day Ukraine.}}</ref>). A personal pistol remained in a drawer, but the professor chose to hang himself. He was buried at the Novodevichy cemetery in Moscow.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/68123592/valeri-alekseevich-legasov |title=Valeri Alekseevich Legasov|website= findagrave.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://novodevichye.com/legasov/ |website=novodevichye.com|title=Legasov's tomb}}</ref>\n\nThis was not Legasov's first suicide attempt.<ref>{{cite web|website=Media Entertainment Arts WorldWide|title=Scientist who exposed true extent of Chernobyl disaster killed himself a day after second anniversary (As the Deputy Director of Kurchatov Institute of Atomic Energy in Moscow, Valery Legasov received a distress call on April 26, 1986, asking him to head to Chernobyl. His life was never the same.)|author=Tripathi, Namrata |date= May 2, 2019 | url=https://meaww.com/hbo-chernobyl-nuclear-disaster-soviet-specialist-valery-legasov-expose-extent}}</ref> [[David R. Marples]] has suggested that the adversity of the Chernobyl disaster on Legasov's psychological state was the factor that led to his decision to die by suicide.<ref name = Marples/> Before his suicide, Legasov wrote documents revealing previously undisclosed facts about the catastrophe.<ref name=\"Spiegel\" /> According to an analysis of the recording for the [[BBC]] TV movie ''Chernobyl Nuclear Disaster'',<ref name=\"BBCdisaster\">{{cite book|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0775665/|title=Surviving Disaster: Chernobyl Nuclear Disaster|publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> Legasov claims political pressure censored the mention of Soviet nuclear secrecy in his report to the IAEA, a secrecy which forbade even plant operators having knowledge of previous accidents and known problems with reactor design.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.world-nuclear.org/information-library/safety-and-security/safety-of-plants/chernobyl-accident.aspx |title = Chernobyl &#124; Chernobyl Accident &#124; Chernobyl Disaster - World Nuclear Association}}</ref> The ''[[Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists]]'' also stated that Legasov had become bitterly disillusioned with the failure of the authorities to confront the design flaws.<ref name=\"the-bulletin\">{{cite journal|title=Chernobyl's Lengthening Shadow |first1=David|last1= Marples |journal=[[The Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists]] |volume=49|issue=7|date=September 1993 |page=40 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pQwAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA40|authorlink1=David R. Marples|bibcode=1993BuAtS..49g..38M|doi=10.1080/00963402.1993.11456385}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nLegasov's suicide caused shockwaves in the Soviet nuclear industry. In particular, the problem with the design of the [[control rod]]s in Chernobyl-type [[RBMK|RBMK reactors]] was rapidly admitted and addressed.<ref name=BBCdisaster /><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.world-nuclear.org/information-library/safety-and-security/safety-of-plants/chernobyl-accident.aspx |title = Chernobyl &#124; Chernobyl Accident &#124; Chernobyl Disaster - World Nuclear Association}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 September 1996, then-Russian president [[Boris Yeltsin]] posthumously conferred on Legasov the honorary title of [[Hero of the Russian Federation]], the country's highest honorary title, for the \"courage and heroism\" shown in his investigation of the disaster.<ref>{{cite book|authors=de Miranda, Paulo Emilio V. | url=https://books.google.com/?id=e5t5DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA352&lpg=PA352&dq=valery+legasov+hero+of+the+russian+federation#v=onepage&q=valery%20legasov%20hero%20of%20the%20russian%20federation&f=false |title= Science and Engineering of Hydrogen-Based Energy Technologies|isbn = 9780128142523|date = 2018-11-12}}</ref>\n\n== In media==\nLegasov is portrayed by [[Ade Edmondson]] in the [[BBC]] [[docudrama]] ''Surviving Disaster'' (2006), and by [[Jared Harris]] in the Sky/HBO miniseries ''[[Chernobyl (miniseries)|Chernobyl]]'' (2019).\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Chernobyl disaster effects]]\n* [[Liquidator (Chernobyl)]]\n* [[List of Chernobyl-related articles]]\n* [[Nuclear and radiation accidents and incidents]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Authority control}}\n{{chernobyl disaster|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Legasov, Valery}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:Heroes of the Russian Federation]]\n[[Category:Lenin Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Full Members of the USSR Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Moscow Institute of Physics and Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Moscow State University faculty]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Chernobyl disaster]]\n[[Category:People from Tula, Russia]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Lenin]]\n[[Category:Scientists who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Soviet chemists]]\n[[Category:20th-century chemists]]\n[[Category:Suicides by hanging in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the USSR State Prize]]\n[[Category:Chernobyl liquidators]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of the Soviet Union members]]\n[[Category:D. Mendeleev University of Chemical Technology of Russia alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Koavf", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eChernobyl disaster", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valery_Legasov"}
